### Description

When using a custom DateAdapter for a date class that doesn't support conversion to primitives (js-joda), that I like because it avoids too many errors. It fails when a date is selected on the date range picker, with the following error:

_Uncaught TypeError: A conversion from Temporal to a number is not allowed. To compare use the methods .equals(), .compareTo(), .isBefore() or one that is more suitable to your use case._

This happen because  the code is using `cell.rawValue` at the following line:

https://github.com/angular/components/blob/1da7f15ff66ce30ad9888d56760bb149c960d2a6/src/material/datepicker/calendar-body.ts#LL515C40-L515C48

I think it should be using `cell.compareValue` instead.

A workaround can be made monkey patching `MatCalendarBody` (remember to use your date class check if not using js-joda)

```typescript
import { MatCalendarBody } from '@angular/material/datepicker';

const originalIsInRange = MatCalendarBody.prototype._isInRange;
MatCalendarBody.prototype._isInRange = function(value: number) {
  const badValue = value as any;
  if (badValue instanceof LocalDate) {
    value = new Date(badValue.year(), badValue.monthValue(), badValue.dayOfMonth()).getTime();
  }
  return originalIsInRange.call(this, value);
};
```

### Reproduction

I am pointing to the exact source line with the problem

### Expected Behavior

Using a custom DateAdapter for js-joda should work. The date range picker should not give an error with clicked.

### Actual Behavior

An exception when a date is clicked and the date class using by the DateAdapter doesn't support conversion to primitives.

